How many poker hands contain all different kinds?

There are 13131313 kinds, so we have \binom{13}{5}(135)\binom{13}{5}(513​) such hands.

But wait, there is more to it: There are 4444 different suits and each of the 5555 cards can be any of these suits.

So actually, we get 4^5\cdot\binom{13}{5}45⋅(135)4^5\cdot\binom{13}{5}45⋅(513​) hands when we take into consideration the different combinations of suits.

Now, how many different poker hands are there in total?

There are 52525252 cards in total, so we have \binom{52}{5}(525)\binom{52}{5}(552​) possible hands.

Consequently, the probability we are interested in is p=\frac{4^5\cdot\binom{13}{5}}{\binom{52}{5}}\approx0.5071p=45⋅(135)(525)≈0.5071p=\frac{4^5\cdot\binom{13}{5}}{\binom{52}{5}}\approx0.5071p=(552​)45⋅(513​)​≈0.5071

To see this, let us compute the probabilities.

E_1 = \{THH, THT, TTH, TTT\} \implies P(E_1) = 4/8 = 1/2E1={THH,THT,TTH,TTT}  ⟹  P(E1)=4/8=1/2E_1 = \{THH, THT, TTH, TTT\} \implies P(E_1) = 4/8 = 1/2E1​={THH,THT,TTH,TTT}⟹P(E1​)=4/8=1/2
E_2 = \{HHH, HHT, THH, THT\} \implies P(E_2) = 4/8 = 1/2E2={HHH,HHT,THH,THT}  ⟹  P(E2)=4/8=1/2E_2 = \{HHH, HHT, THH, THT\} \implies P(E_2) = 4/8 = 1/2E2​={HHH,HHT,THH,THT}⟹P(E2​)=4/8=1/2

\implies P(E_1)P(E_2) = 1/4  ⟹  P(E1)P(E2)=1/4\implies P(E_1)P(E_2) = 1/4⟹P(E1​)P(E2​)=1/4.

Now E_1\cap E_2E1∩E2E_1\cap E_2E1​∩E2​ consists of the outcomes \{THH, THT\}{THH,THT}\{THH, THT\}{THH,THT} so P(E_1\cap E_2)=2/8=1/4P(E1∩E2)=2/8=1/4P(E_1\cap E_2)=2/8=1/4P(E1​∩E2​)=2/8=1/4.

In total, P(E_1\cap E_2) = P(E_1)P(E_2)P(E1∩E2)=P(E1)P(E2)P(E_1\cap E_2) = P(E_1)P(E_2)P(E1​∩E2​)=P(E1​)P(E2​) so the two events are independent.

7

Let's take (b):

Reflexive?
No because 0\cdot 0=0<10⋅0=0<10\cdot 0=0<10⋅0=0<1 so 0\nsim00≁00\nsim00≁0.

Symmetric?
If xy\geq1xy≥1xy\geq1xy≥1 then clearly yx\geq1yx≥1yx\geq1yx≥1 because xy=yxxy=yxxy=yxxy=yx so yes the relation is symmetric.

Anti-symmetric?
No. For example 2\sim32∼32\sim32∼3 and 3\sim 23∼23\sim 23∼2 but 2\neq 32≠32\neq 32=3.

Bonus question: can a relation be both symmetric and anti-symmetric at the same time?

Transisitve?

Suppose x\sim yx∼yx\sim yx∼y and y\sim zy∼zy\sim zy∼z. That is xy\geq 1xy≥1xy\geq 1xy≥1 and yz\geq 1yz≥1yz\geq 1yz≥1. From xy\geq 1xy≥1xy\geq 1xy≥1 we know that both xxxx and yyyy must be non-zero and have the same sign. From yz\geq 1yz≥1yz\geq 1yz≥1 we know that both yyyy and zzzz must be non-zero and have the same sign. Hence, x,yx,yx,yx,y and zzzz are all non-zero and have the same sign. Therefore xz\geq 1xz≥1xz\geq 1xz≥1 as well. So yes, the relation is transisitve.

Actually, the relation can be re-formulated as follows: x\sim y\iff \operatorname{sign}(x)=\operatorname{sign}(y)\text{ and } x,y\neq0x∼y  ⟺  sign⁡(x)=sign⁡(y) and x,y≠0x\sim y\iff \operatorname{sign}(x)=\operatorname{sign}(y)\text{ and } x,y\neq0x∼y⟺sign(x)=sign(y) and x,y=0.

I'll do a) and b) together:

A relation on SSSS is a subset of S\times SS×SS\times SS×S. In other words, a relation RRRR is the same as an element of the power set \mathcal{P}(S\times S)P(S×S)\mathcal{P}(S\times S)P(S×S) of S\times SS×SS\times SS×S.

So the total number of relations on SSSS is |\mathcal{P}(S\times S)|=2^{|S\times S|} = 2^{n^2}∣P(S×S)∣=2∣S×S∣=2n2|\mathcal{P}(S\times S)|=2^{|S\times S|} = 2^{n^2}∣P(S×S)∣=2∣S×S∣=2n2.

A relation RRRR with (a,b)\notin R(a,b)∉R(a,b)\notin R(a,b)∈/R is a subset of S\setminus\{a\}\times S\setminus\{b\}S∖{a}×S∖{b}S\setminus\{a\}\times S\setminus\{b\}S∖{a}×S∖{b}.

We have |\mathcal{P}(S\setminus\{a\}\times S\setminus\{b\})|=2^{|S\setminus\{a\}\times S\setminus\{b\}|}=2^{(n-1)^2}∣P(S∖{a}×S∖{b})∣=2∣S∖{a}×S∖{b}∣=2(n−1)2|\mathcal{P}(S\setminus\{a\}\times S\setminus\{b\})|=2^{|S\setminus\{a\}\times S\setminus\{b\}|}=2^{(n-1)^2}∣P(S∖{a}×S∖{b})∣=2∣S∖{a}×S∖{b}∣=2(n−1)2 such subsets.

That is, there are 2^{(n-1)^2}2(n−1)22^{(n-1)^2}2(n−1)2 relations on RRRR with (a,b)\notin R(a,b)∉R(a,b)\notin R(a,b)∈/R. This answers b).

A relation either contains (a,b)(a,b)(a,b)(a,b) or not. So to find the number of relations containing (a,b)(a,b)(a,b)(a,b) we take the total number of relations and subtract the number of those relations not containing (a,b)(a,b)(a,b)(a,b).

That is, there are 2^{n^2} - 2^{(n-1)^2} = 2^{n^2}(1-2^{1-2n})2n2−2(n−1)2=2n2(1−21−2n)2^{n^2} - 2^{(n-1)^2} = 2^{n^2}(1-2^{1-2n})2n2−2(n−1)2=2n2(1−21−2n) relations containing (a,b)(a,b)(a,b)(a,b). This answers a).

a)

Let R=(r_{ij})R=(rij)R=(r_{ij})R=(rij​) with r_{ij}\in\{0,1\}rij∈{0,1}r_{ij}\in\{0,1\}rij​∈{0,1} be a symmetric relation. This is the same as saying that the matrix is symmetric. Therefore we need to count the number of symmetric n\times nn×nn\times nn×n-matrices:
